---
/** Hub: state estate & inheritance tax. Worked example + state tables from the dataset. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import StateDeathTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/StateDeathTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { stateEstateTax, stateInheritanceTax } from '../../lib/state-death-tax';
import { stateDeathTax } from '../../data/state-inheritance';
import { states } from '../../data/states';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const orEstate = stateEstateTax('OR', 2000000);
const paInh = stateInheritanceTax('PA', 100000, 'sibling');
const estateStates = Object.entries(stateDeathTax)
  .filter(([, r]) => r.hasEstateTax)
  .map(([c, r]) => ({ name: states[c]?.name ?? c, exemption: r.estateExemption, topRate: r.estateTopRate }))
  .sort((a, b) => (a.exemption ?? 0) - (b.exemption ?? 0));
const inheritanceStates = Object.entries(stateDeathTax)
  .filter(([, r]) => r.hasInheritanceTax)
  .map(([c]) => states[c]?.name ?? c);
---

<Base
  title="State estate & inheritance tax calculator 2026"
  description="Which states tax estates and inheritances in 2026. 13 states plus DC have an estate tax, 5 an inheritance tax — some from as little as $1 million."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>State estate &amp; inheritance tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The federal estate tax spares almost everyone. State death taxes start as low as $1 million — and hit far more estates.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Two state taxes the federal $15 million exemption hides. An <strong>estate tax</strong>
    is paid by the estate on value above a state exemption — {estateStates.length} states
    have one, and Oregon's starts at just {formatMoney(1000000)}. An <strong>inheritance
    tax</strong> is paid by the heir, at a rate that depends on the relationship —
    {inheritanceStates.length} states have one. This shows both for your state.
  </p>

  <StateDeathTaxCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked examples</h2>
  <p>
    A {formatMoney(2000000)} estate in Oregon, and a {formatMoney(100000)} inheritance
    by a sibling in Pennsylvania — two states, two different taxes:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Situation</th><th>Tax</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Oregon estate tax on a {formatMoney(2000000)} estate</td><td>{formatMoney(orEstate.estimatedTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pennsylvania inheritance tax, {formatMoney(100000)} to a sibling (12%)</td><td>{formatMoney(paInh.estimatedTax)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Oregon taxes the {formatMoney(1000000)} above its {formatMoney(1000000)} exemption,
    for {formatMoney(orEstate.estimatedTax)} — an estate that owes nothing federally.
    Pennsylvania charges a sibling 12% of a {formatMoney(100000)} inheritance,
    {formatMoney(paInh.estimatedTax)}; a spouse would pay nothing and a child 4.5%.
    Relationship is everything with inheritance tax.
  </p>

  <h2>States with an estate tax (2026)</h2>
  <p>Lowest exemption first — these are the estates most likely to be caught:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>State</th><th>Exemption</th><th>Top rate</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {estateStates.map((s) => (
        <tr><td>{s.name}</td><td>{formatMoney(s.exemption ?? 0)}</td><td>{formatPct(s.topRate ?? 0)}</td></tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The {inheritanceStates.length} states with an <em>inheritance</em> tax are
    {' '}{inheritanceStates.join(', ')} — Maryland is the only state with both.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What's the difference between estate and inheritance tax?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Estate tax is paid by the estate, out of its total value, before anything is
      distributed. Inheritance tax is paid by each heir on what they personally
      receive, at a rate set by their relationship to the deceased — spouses and
      children are usually exempt or low-rate, distant heirs pay the most.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Which states have the lowest exemptions?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Oregon at {formatMoney(1000000)} is the lowest, then Rhode Island (~{formatMoney(1838056)})
      and Massachusetts ({formatMoney(2000000)}). At these levels a paid-off home plus
      retirement savings can be enough to owe state estate tax while owing nothing
      federally — the reason state death taxes matter far more to ordinary families.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why is Washington's rate so high?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Washington's top estate-tax rate rose to 35% (the highest in the nation) for
      deaths from July 2025, but reverts to 20% for deaths from July 2026 — so a 2026
      death is 35% in the first half of the year and 20% in the second. The calculator
      uses the first-half rate; confirm the date of death.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does my state have a death tax at all?</h3>
    <p>
      Most likely not — 34 states have neither. Pick your state above and the
      calculator tells you. If it has neither, only the federal estate tax could
      apply, and that spares all but the largest estates.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/estate-tax-calculator/">Federal estate tax calculator</a> — the $15M exclusion</li>
    <li><a href="/inheritance-tax-calculator/">Inheritance tax calculator</a> — the federal income side</li>
    <li><a href="/trust-tax-calculator/">Trust income tax calculator</a> — Form 1041</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. State estate tax uses the top rate over the
    exemption; true schedules are graduated. New York's cliff and Washington's
    mid-year change are noted, not modeled. Not tax or legal advice.
  </p>
</Base>
